{{Politics of Guyana}}
The '''House of Assembly''' was the legislature of [[British Guiana]] in the 1950s and 1960s.
==History== The House of Assembly was established as a result of the [[Waddington Commission]], which led to the enactment of constitutional reforms in 1952; universal suffrage was introduced and the [[Legislative Council (British Guiana)|Legislative Council]] was to be replaced by the House of Assembly. The new House had 28 members; 24 members elected in single member constituencies, a speaker appointed by the Governor and three ex officio members (the Chief Secretary, the Attorney General and the Financial Secretary).<ref name=P/> The term of the final Legislative Council was extended in order to allow preparations for [[British Guiana general election, 1953|elections]] under the new system on 27 April 1953.<ref name=P>[http://parliament.gov.gy/GUYANA%20PARLIAMENT%20HISTORY%202009-1.pdf Historical information events and dates on the Parliament of Guyana from 1718 to 2006] Parliament of Guyana</ref>
The elections were won by the [[People's Progressive Party (Guyana)|People's Progressive Party]] (PPP) led by [[Cheddi Jagan]], who became Prime Minister, whilst [[Eustace Gordon Woolford]] was appointed Speaker of the new House. Its first meeting was held on 18 May.<ref name=P/> After assuming power Jagan embarked on implementing a series of policies that involved radical social reform, mainly directed at the colonial oligarchy. The British colonial authorities sent in troops in response to the alleged threat of a [[Marxism|Marxist]] revolution. [[List of Governors of British Guiana|Governor]] [[Alfred Savage]] suspended the constitution on 9 October (only 133 days after it had come into force);<ref name=N1>[[Dieter Nohlen|Nohlen, D]] (2005) ''Elections in the Americas: A data handbook, Volume I'', p354 {{ISBN|978-0-19-928357-6}}</ref> the House of Assembly was prorogued, before being dissolved on 21 December. A wholly appointed Interim Legislative Council was established in place of the Assembly.
Constitutional reforms in 1964 led to the re-establishment of the House of Assembly as a replacement for the [[bicameralism|bicameral]] [[Legislature (British Guiana)|Legislature]], which had been created in 1961. The new House was a 54-seat body, consisting of 53 elected members and the Speaker. The [[British Guiana general election, 1964|elections]] were held on 7 December 1964 using proportional representation to allocate the seats, and although the PPP won the most seats, the [[People's National Congress (Guyana)|People's National Congress]] (PNC) and [[The United Force|United Force]] were able to form a coalition government with a working majority. Despite losing the elections, Jagan refused to resign as Prime Minister, and had to be removed by [[List of Governors of British Guiana|Governor]] [[Richard Luyt]], with [[Forbes Burnham]] replacing him.<ref>Nohlen, p363</ref> The new House met for the first time on 31 December, although the meeting was boycotted by the PPP.<ref name=P/> [[Aubrey Percival Alleyne]] of the PNC was elected Speaker, and subsequently vacated his seat, allowing [[Philip Duncan (Guyanese politician)|Philip Duncan]] of the PNC to take his place.
On 26 May 1966 the country became independent under the name of [[Guyana]]. A new constitution came into force, replacing the House of Assembly with the [[National Assembly (Guyana)|National Assembly]].
